WEBVTT

p01
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.205
A caller says they can't sign in.

p02
00:00:02.748 --> 00:00:05.636
Before you change a thing, fix the order in your head.

p03
00:00:06.042 --> 00:00:09.872
Cheapest checks first, because two of them clear most of these tickets.

p04
00:00:10.231 --> 00:00:13.120
And in the demo tenant, you never reset a password.

p05
00:00:13.537 --> 00:00:15.687
Start with the three fields.

p06
00:00:15.687 --> 00:00:19.633
Every WashCentral sign-in wants an email, a password, and a tenant code.

p07
00:00:19.633 --> 00:00:22.743
That third one is where logins quietly fail.

p08
00:00:22.743 --> 00:00:27.774
A wrong tenant code sends a perfectly good account to the wrong company's data,

p09
00:00:27.774 --> 00:00:28.760
and nothing happens.

p10
00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:32.240
Confirm the tenant before you ever suspect the password.

p11
00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:33.632
Now one question.

p12
00:00:33.632 --> 00:00:35.616
Did this client come from WashAssist?

p13
00:00:35.616 --> 00:00:37.950
If so, their login never changed.

p14
00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:40.170
Same username, same password, same tenant.

p15
00:00:40.170 --> 00:00:44.795
A migrated user who can't get in is almost never a credentials problem.

p16
00:00:44.795 --> 00:00:50.958
Have them try their old login first, and you may have skipped a reset you shouldn't be making.

p17
00:00:51.416 --> 00:00:52.946
Open System Users, under Settings.

p18
00:00:52.946 --> 00:00:56.725
This is the master list of everyone who can sign in.

p19
00:00:56.725 --> 00:01:00.828
Eight columns, and four of them answer a login ticket by themselves.

p20
00:01:00.828 --> 00:01:05.627
There's a search across the top, and a New Record button you leave alone.

p21
00:01:05.627 --> 00:01:06.851
We're only reading here.

p22
00:01:07.347 --> 00:01:09.498
First, does the account even exist?

p23
00:01:09.911 --> 00:01:14.071
Search by name, code, or email instead of scrolling a long list.

p24
00:01:14.544 --> 00:01:20.314
No match usually means the wrong tenant again, or a user who was never finished being set up.

p25
00:01:20.737 --> 00:01:25.040
And if the rows won't load, that's the data service, not an empty tenant.

p26
00:01:25.468 --> 00:01:27.007
Read the Active column.

p27
00:01:27.389 --> 00:01:30.910
If it's switched off, the account can't sign in, full stop.

p28
00:01:31.328 --> 00:01:35.242
And to the caller, a disabled account looks exactly like a bad password.

p29
00:01:36.299 --> 00:01:40.614
Re-enabling it is an admin's job in production, not yours in the demo.

p30
00:01:41.041 --> 00:01:41.903
Next column: S-S-O.

p31
00:01:42.233 --> 00:01:43.463
If that reads yes, the password doesn't even live in WashCentral.

p32
00:01:43.765 --> 00:01:49.459
It's held by the identity provider.

p33
00:01:49.663 --> 00:01:51.890
Reset it here and nothing changes.

p34
00:01:52.143 --> 00:01:56.720
So stop the password thread and send it to the single sign-on integration page instead.

p35
00:01:57.157 --> 00:01:58.885
Then Last Login.

p36
00:01:59.720 --> 00:02:05.149
A recent date tells you the account works,

p37
00:02:05.828 --> 00:02:08.063
so today's failure is probably a typo or the tenant code.

p38
00:02:08.433 --> 00:02:10.349
A blank tells you it never signed in, which fits a setup that was never finished.

p39
00:02:10.888 --> 00:02:13.680
One column, and you know whether this ever worked.

p40
00:02:14.118 --> 00:02:14.883
Last check.

p41
00:02:15.292 --> 00:02:18.194
Open the Audit menu, then User Activity.

p42
00:02:18.871 --> 00:02:23.071
Failed logins show up as one tile at the top, a count for the whole tenant.

p43
00:02:23.601 --> 00:02:27.940
There is no per user failure column, so read the caller's own row instead:

p44
00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.908
status, last login, logins this month.

p45
00:02:31.490 --> 00:02:35.335
A quiet row during a tenant wide spike points back at the tenant code,

p46
00:02:35.561 --> 00:02:39.040
and the event by event trail lives next door in the Audit Log.

p47
00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.633
By now you know whether a reset is even the fix.

p48
00:02:43.175 --> 00:02:44.272
You don't do it here.

p49
00:02:44.869 --> 00:02:46.809
In production there are two doors:

p50
00:02:47.185 --> 00:02:50.020
the user resets themselves with Forgot Password,

p51
00:02:50.434 --> 00:02:53.337
or an admin resets it from that user's own record.

p52
00:02:54.024 --> 00:02:56.247
If it's a single sign-on account, it's neither.

p53
00:02:56.627 --> 00:02:58.778
That fix lives with the identity provider.

p54
00:02:59.304 --> 00:03:00.506
If none of that lands it, escalate clean.

p55
00:03:00.864 --> 00:03:01.961
Username, tenant, the timestamps of the failures,

p56
00:03:02.329 --> 00:03:07.688
and screenshots with anything sensitive masked.

p57
00:03:07.933 --> 00:03:09.229
Never the password.

p58
00:03:09.957 --> 00:03:13.907
The next tier should be able to reproduce it without calling the customer back.

p59
00:03:14.400 --> 00:03:15.545
That's the whole flow.

p60
00:03:16.041 --> 00:03:17.778
Three fields and the tenant code.

p61
00:03:18.102 --> 00:03:19.453
The migration question.

p62
00:03:20.141 --> 00:03:24.607
Then System Users for active, single sign-on, and last login.

p63
00:03:25.321 --> 00:03:27.613
Then User Activity for the failures.

p64
00:03:28.033 --> 00:03:31.267
A reset only in production, or a clean escalation.

p65
00:03:31.696 --> 00:03:35.675
Cheap checks first, every time, and nothing in the demo touched.

